On Thu, 9 Feb 1995 05:10:35 -0600 Jamie Hoglund said:
>Hello all,
>
>I'm a fairly new rexx programmer for OS/2, and I'd like to be able to use
>rexx under my unix account.
>
>I understand Unix has rexx, something like regina, but how do I
>write a rexx script under unix?
>
>Do I just put /*rexx*/ in the first line?
>
>I tried:
>/*rexx*/
>SAY "Hello Rexx"
>
>but that didn't work under unix. How do I tell if a system supports rexx?
>
Ask someone who knows :-)

You don't say what unix or what REXX.  Assuming your system has REXX,
here are a couple of suggestions:
  1. Assuming your rexx interpreter is any_rexx (regina, rexx/6000...)
     Execute the interpreter and pass it the name of the exec thusly:
     /usr/local/bin/any_rexx my_exec_name (parameters ...)
     substituting the appropriate path name and exec name.
  2. Code the first line of the exec as:
     #! /usr/local/bin/rexx
     again using the correct path name for the interpreter.  This
     should be the first line beginning in col 1, before any rexx
     comments.  CHMOD the exec to executable and execute it by:
     ./my_exec_name (parameters...)

As you can see, you have to at least know what interpreter you're using.
You should get the information from your sysadmin or whatever.
Failing this, poke around /usr/bin and /usr/local/bin and other likely
places to see what's available.

