jhoglund@mirage.skypoint.com (Jamie Hoglund) writes:


>Hello all,

>I'm a fairly new rexx programmer for OS/2, and I'd like to be able to use
>rexx under my unix account.

>I understand Unix has rexx, something like regina, but how do I
>write a rexx script under unix?

>Do I just put /*rexx*/ in the first line?

>I tried:
>/*rexx*/
>SAY "Hello Rexx"

No. Like all shell scripts you start the script with:

#!/path_to_shell_command/shell_command

So if you have Regina in /opt/bin, the first line of your script would be:

#!/opt/bin/rexx

The script file must also be executable for whoever is running it.
The other alternative is to run the script explicitly with the "rexx"
command:

% rexx script_file

>but that didn't work under unix. How do I tell if a system supports rexx?

Simply by looking for an executable that will interpret REXX code.

